<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFB4FFEE6DC2FD08FEB5A9E7" pageId="16" pageNumber="1529" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFB4FFEE6DC2FD08FEB5A9E7" blockId="16.[178,1086,661,741]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1529">
Etymology: The trivial name 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB4FFEE6F5AFD08FDE4A9A8" box="[554,625,661,682]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1529">similus</emphasis>
stems from 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB4FFEE6F83FD08FCA0A9A8" box="[755,821,661,682]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1529">similis</emphasis>
(= like), is a Latin adjective. I refer to the shared superficial similarity between the members of this species and congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
